      The dataset concerns car fuel consumption.

          cylinders(cyl): multi-valued discrete 
          displacement(disp): continuous 
          horsepower(hp): continuous

          acceleration(acc): continuous
          modelyear(yr): multi-valued discrete 
          origin(origin): multi-valued discrete 
          car_name(car_name): string (unique for each instance)

       Out of the 398 rows 6 have NaN in the hp column. We can drop those 6 rows. Not a good idea under all situations
       Instead of dropping the rows, lets replace the missing values with median value.

       Machine Learning algorithms can typically only have numerical values as their independent variables. Hence label encoding is   quite pivotal as they encode categorical labels with appropriate numerical values.
       Origins (categorical) are converted to numerical using pd.dummies function.
       Note that, we have introduced the three more columns for the better analysis

      q25, q75 = np.percentile(df['mpg'], 25), np.percentile(mpg_df['mpg'], 75)

      # From the univariant analysis the below points are observed,
          The acceleration of the cars in the data is normally distributed and most of the cars have an acceleration of 15 m/s2 (assume displacement in 'metre' and time in 'seconds'.
          Half of the total number of cars (51.3%) in the data have 4 cylinders.
          Our output/dependent variable (mpg) is slightly skewed to the right.
              
          It could be a problem for a linear regression that the objective variable mpg does not follow a normal distribution.  
          Also, there are very few records that have a value of 3 or 5 as 'cyl',implying the possibility of an insufficient sample size to withdraw a significant result.

      From the univariant analysis the below points are observed,

      The acceleration of the cars in the data is normally distributed and most of the cars have an acceleration of 15 m/s2 (assume displacement in 'metre' and time in 'seconds'.
Half of the total number of cars (51.3%) in the data have 4 cylinders.
Our output/dependent variable (mpg) is slightly skewed to the right.

It could be a problem for a linear regression that the objective variable mpg does not follow a normal distribution.  
Also, there are very few records that have a value of 3 or 5 as 'cyl',implying the possibility of an insufficient sample size to withdraw a significant result.

      # From the bivariate and multivariate analysis the below points are observed,  
          # one can find the pair of disp-wt show extremely high correlation.
          # In general that the displacement of a car highly affects the weight of the car.
          # 'disp-hp'and 'hp-wt' follow this correlation with a close value.
          # These are also appropriate since both displacement and horsepower are determined by the engine type.
          # 'mpg' indicates an inverse quadratic relationship between disp, hp,and wt.
          # This relationship also can be explained by general knowledge that a heavy(or sporty) car is highly likely to be a fuel wasting car or less mileage car.
          # Among  the  continuous  variable, 'acc' is  only the one which does not show a strong correlation between the others.  
          # However,since the parameter of horsepower rules the driving force of the car, it seems reasonable that acceleration 
          has the lowest negative correlation index between horsepower.

      # Relationship between 'mpg' and other features
          We can see that there is a relationship between the mpg variable and the other variables and this satisfies the first assumption of Linear regression.
          There is a strong negative correlation between the displacement,horsepower,weight,and cylinders.This implies that,as any one of those variables increases,the mpg decreases.
          The displacement,horsepower,weight,and cylinders have a strong positive correlations between themselves and it voilates the non-multicollinearity assumption of Linear regression.
          Multicollinearity hinders the performance and accuracy of our regression model.To avoid this, we have to get rid of some of these variables by doing feature selection.
          The other variables.ie.acceleration,model and origin are not highly correlated with each other

      Relationship between 'mpg' and other features

      We can see that there is a relationship between the mpg variable and the other variables and this satisfies the first assumption of Linear regression.
There is a strong negative correlation between the displacement,horsepower,weight,and cylinders.This implies that,as any one of those variables increases,the mpg decreases.
The displacement,horsepower,weight,and cylinders have a strong positive correlations between themselves and it voilates the non-multicollinearity assumption of Linear regression.
Multicollinearity hinders the performance and accuracy of our regression model.To avoid this, we have to get rid of some of these variables by doing feature selection.
The other variables.ie.acceleration,model and origin are not highly correlated with each other

      # How using different models for different clusters will be helpful in this case and how it will be different than using one single model without clustering? Mention how it impacts performance and prediction.

      How using different models for different clusters will be helpful in this case and how it will be different than using one single model without clustering? Mention how it impacts performance and prediction.

       
      # Different models for different clusters are NOT helping in the given dataset.
      # From the above "Regression Model Score summary", it is understood that Single model without clustering performs better than the different clusters
      # Eventhough we are able to create the three clusters, with respect to predict the target variable ('mpg'), model for different clusters are NOT performing better.
      # Generally, more data will help the model to learn for the better prediction.
      # In this case study, data in the clusters are less. Hence it impacts the performance more.
       
      # Improvisation:

      Improvisation:

       
      Quality: Quality of the data is pretty decent except for just '?' missing values, rest of them are fine. Suggestion if the data collection team could also collect the variants of the same car manufactures, that would certainly help in knowing how originwise performance. 
      Quantity:Quantity of the data was not sufficient to create the valued clusters. Suggestion would be to collect more and more data.
      Variety: Unsupervised learning method which deals with NOT only structured data. But as far as variety of the data is concerned, it is always helpful to collect more and more data in any form that we could. Like, it may be helpful if the data collection team could collect some more data related to milege. 
      Velocity: Since we are not doing any real-time analysis. So it would be difficult to comment on the velocity of the data. But as far as the entire process is concerned, it is always beneficial to collect the data as fast as possible, so that we could come up with better strategies to target the milege in any road situations. Data would be of no use if it gets outdated and then it would be difficult to predict mileage today based on outdated data. 
      Veracity: Since the data has been provided by the company itself, hence the data is completely authentic. As far as noise and abnormalities in the data are concerned, the abnormalities that we saw in the data is not because of the inauthentic data but due to their own nature.
